project.name: Polluck Inspired
project.notes: THE BACKGROUND I set my background to black using set background command. I created a block using the color palettes I made. Since my color palette functions draw larger lines, it felt like a part of the background, so that's the name of the block. The background block starts with clearing the stage, and setting it up. There is a set up block that lifts the pen from previous code, sets the pen size, points the pen to the right of the stage and places the the pen down. The random position block, created by having the go to x and y command filled with picking random postion left and right and top and bottom of the stage, is used before each palette line is drawn. The postion and palette block- that specific order (of all three palettes), is placed in a repeat command. It's repeated 3 times to cover a majority of the stage. THE LAYERS The next block created is called Layers. It includes the created blocks for the random polka dots and slush lines. Both of these blocks are used twice so it doesn't feel like there is a true top layer. The random polka dots block is created by placing a 'change the pen hue by __ (20)' command, 'random position' command, and a custom 'dot size' block. The repeat amount is filled with a variable so that this is a parameter. The Dot size block is created by using the 'set pen size to (variable: size)' command, pen down, move (zero- for dot) steps, pen up. The rainbow slush block was created by placing the 'set pen size (1)' command and 'point in direction (random' command. In a 'repeat' command, the commands 'change pen hue by (10), random position, and line length are placed. The repeat amount is an amount variable. This command is warped since I wanted to use it for an enormous amount of little lines. Line length is a custom block that creates one line. It is created by placing pen down, using the move command with variable length and then pulling the pen back up. There is a set up circle block which picks the pen up, uses the commands, 'set pen size to (3)', 'set the pen hue to (color orange)' [selected from the color palette, using the custom reporter 'color ___'], 'point in direction (135)', and 'go to x:(180) y:(130)'. The color orange reporter was create using the report command filled with the 'item (2) of' block, filled with the 'assoc (color)' filled with 'list' of multiple list that name the color and give the number that corresponds on the spectrum. The list of list creates a table. Circle is a custom block created by placing a 'move (variable: size) steps' command and 'turn (10) degrees' command in a 'repeat (36)' command. By creating the size variable, the circles size is a manipulatable parameter. THE PALETTES The purple palette is a mirror of the colors from left to right. The blue palette is shades of blue. The color palette is of the rainbow. The blue and purple color palettes were created by using the 'set pen color to' command and the 'pen hue' reporter. I choose a shade of the color I wanted and then used the reporter to tell me what number responded to that color on the spectrum. I used the list function and placed the number reported along with very close in value numbers to get different shades of the same color. For the color palette, I used numbers that captured the entire color spectrum to get a rainbow palette. A variable was created titled __ palette. The list function was then placed into the 'set (enter variable; __ palette) to (enter corresponding list)'. Once this command is clicked, the variable is a representation of the list that represents the colors. To graph the color palettes, the command 'for 'i' - to "length of '__ palette'"' is used. You enter the 'set pen hue to 'item 'i' of '___ palette''' and a move command with the desired amount of steps to create a line of your array of colors.

block-definition.comment: Reports a new list whose items are the same as in the input list, except that if two or more equal items appear in the input list, only the last one is kept in the result.

Reports a sorted version of the list in its first input slot, using the comparison function in the second input slot. For a list of numbers, using < as the comparison function will sort from low to high; using > will sort from high to low.

The second input is an "association list," a list of two-item lists. Each of those smaller lists has a "key" as its first item and a "value" as its second. ASSOC reports the first key-value pair in the association list whose key matches the first input.

This block carries out the given script for each item of the given list, like the primitive FOR EACH. What's different is that it provides the # variable, which will contain the item number in the list of each item in turn, 1 while processing item 1, and so on.
Takes a (possibly deep) list as input, and reports a human-readable text form of the list (namely, Lisp notation). Will not work on circular lists.

SENTENCE is the main constructor for sentences, represented as lists of words. It takes zero or more inputs, each of which can be either a list or a text string. If a list, the input is assumed to be a list of words. If a text string, it is converted to a list of words using SENTENCE→LIST. Then all the lists of words are appended to form a new list of words. If the inputs are lists of lists rather than lists of words, SENTENCE, like APPEND, does only one level of flattening, reporting a list of all the items of all the input lists.

ZIP takes any number of lists as inputs. The lists should all be the same length. ZIP reports a list of lists in which the first item is a list of all the first items, the second item is a list of all the second items, etc. Viewing the inputs as the rows of a matrix, ZIP reports its transpose.
The identity function reports its input.

Takes as input a function of N inputs and N lists. The function is called with item 1 of all the lists as its inputs, with item 2 of all the lists as its inputs, and so on. (The lists should all be the same length.)
Takes a sentence in text string form and reports the sentence as a list of its words.
